"Standard 28-pin 16Kx8 ROM"
"but original 16K Atari ROMs are on 2x chips"

"Before around 1983, four 4116 chips were cheaper than a single 4416
solely because 4416 wasn't widely produced or priced lower yet."

"The Commodore 64 initially used eight 64kx1 DRAM chips, but in the mid-80s,
the cost-reduced redesign used two 64kx4 chips (256kbit, 4 data lines) instead."

"Around 1987, 256kbit replaced 64kbit in turn, so computers like the
Commodore 64 started using two of them for 64Kbyte."


16Kx4 DRAM (TMS4416, IMS2620)

• 1983 Timex-Sinclair TS2068 (as main memory)
• 1984 Commodore 16 (for 16K main memory)
• 1985 Commodore C128 (for 16K video memory)
• 1989 Philips NSC 800 (for 16K video memory)

TI introduced the first 16K x 4 as TMS 4416 in 1980.
Still it took until 1983/84 until they became widely available;
at that time 64 KB RAM was the way to go for new designs.

"BYTE 1985-12, listed at $4.95, compared to 4164 same speed grade $0.69"


