By 1984, 16K×4 devices were already volume parts from:
Texas Instruments – TMS4416
Hitachi – HM50416P
NEC – μPD41416C
Fujitsu – MB81416
Mostek – MK4516 / MK4164-4 (naming overlap)
They were used in:
Video RAM banks in late-generation arcade boards (e.g., Namco, Sega pre-’85)
16-bit VRAM → 4 chips (32K)
Available in 1K lots, not as cheaply as 64K×1


"TI TMS 4116-20 -> 200ns access, 375ns cycle time in 1977;
Hitatchi 4716A-2 -> 200ns access, 320ns cycle in 1979;
Mitsubishi M5K4116S-2 -> 120ns access, 280ns cycle in 1979.
All access as average, cycle as maximum. I just picked some pre 1980 databooks from the shelf.
Similar for 64k: Mitsubishi M5K4164 with 120ns/220ns in 1979 and INMOS as well." – Raffzahn


