Rev-A: 16 x 16Kx1 + 8 x 16Kx1  (4116, 24 ICs)                      •• first run
Rev-B:  8 x 32Kx1 + 8 x 16Kx1  (4532+4116, half-bad 4164s, 16 ICs) •• most likely rev
Rev-C:  4 x 16Kx4 + 2 x 16Kx4  (4416, entirely 16Kx4s)             •• only used as VRAM
Rev-D:  4 x 64Kx1 + 2 x 16Kx4  (4164+4416, 2x cycle time)          •• like Electron
Rev-E:  8 x 64Kx1 + 4 x 64Kx1  (4164 "Plus" edition)               •• upgrade model, 64+32K

Half-Bad 64Kx1:
CoCo "later" rev used half-bad 4164s; HIGH/LOW jumper.
ZX Spectrum "Upper RAM" TMS4532-15NL3, TMS4532-15NL4, OKI M3732H-20, M3732L-20



BOM Study

If you do a custom VDP in a foundry and amortize NRE across 100k units the per-unit mask/fab cost
can fall into single-digit dollars; exact depends on process, masks and yields. If you instead
buy an off-the-shelf VDP like a TMS9918, that chip in that era would be in the mid-teens per unit—
more expensive than a well-amortized custom ASIC at 100k.)

100K+ MOQ contract prices:
Rockwell/Synertek 6502 "were inexpensive in high volume" ~$2.50
4164 (64Kx1 µpd4164-1 410ns 5V TS) DRAM @500ns — US$1.50 each – US$12.00
4116 (16K×1 HM4816A-4/MB8118-12 270ns 5V TS) DRAM @280ns — US$0.40 each – US$3.20
Custom VDP (standard-cell ASIC) per-unit — amortized at 100k — US$6.00–US$10.00 (~$8)
74LS glue (138, 244, 374, 245, 273, etc) ~10 chips, US$0.12 each – US$1.20
16K mask ROM (2x8K HN48364 350ns) (cheaper at high volume) — per unit — US$1.50
Oscillator/crystal 14.31818 MHz + small passives — US$1.20
Board-level miscellaneous (connectors, small discrete parts) — US$2.00
TOTAL – US$31.59

PCB assembly (parts placement, soldering, test): $6–$10 per board at high volume (contract EMS)
Plastic case, power supply, packaging, manual: $6–$8 (very cheap box & PSU can be sourced cheaply)
Board-level testing / QA / burn-in: $2–$4
Contingency, logistics, factory markup (component procurement overhead, scrap, warranty reserve): $3–$6

realistic total BOM / factory cost in the vicinity of:
• Low assembly & lean packaging scenario: $28.60 + $6 + $6 + $2 + $3 = $45.60
• Mid assembly & mid packaging scenario: $28.60 + $8 + $7 + $3 + $4.50 = $51.50
• More conservative assembly & packaging: $28.60 + $10 + $8 + $4 + $6 = $56.60

16K×4 (64Kbit, 4-bit) = $0.80 per chip (reasonable high-volume estimate)
16K×4 x4 (32K) or x6 (48K)

At 100k+ volumes you should be able to secure 16K×4 devices at good prices, but confirm
lead times and second sources.

Goldmine:
https://bitsavers.computerhistory.org/components/hitachi/_dataBooks/
https://bitsavers.computerhistory.org/components/fujitsu/_dataBooks/

Hitachi: "it is recommended to insert large capacitors (a 10 µF capacitor for every 9
pieces of 64K-bit HM4864P, for example) as well as a 0.1 µF capacitor having good
high-frequency characteristics for each memory." [between ICs and voltage supply]

Hitachi: Don't connect input of ICs directly to ground to fix input as "H" level.

"Specify power & thermal margin on your board so the vendor can confirm which grades
and power clamps are safe at your operating temperature."

Those slow (410-450ns) grades were typically lower-cost, lower-test-grade offerings
from NEC, Toshiba, Mitsubishi, Mostek/TI and legacy/clone houses.

Get an allocation quote from the vendor you already plan to use (Hitachi/Fujitsu)
• Ask them explicitly for the slowest bin they will supply in 4164 (or a 64K×1 variant)
  and for commodity pricing at 100k MOQ. Vendors sometimes hold older process runs as
  “commercial” or “automotive” grades that aren’t advertised prominently. If they can’t
  supply, they can often recommend a sister fab or partner who can. (Negotiating this
  with your existing VRAM supplier is the lowest-risk path.)
• NEC, Toshiba, Mitsubishi: historically supplied slow/cheap bins for large OEMs,
  and supplied single-rail 4164 parts.

100,000/8 = 12,500 units
160,000/8 = 20,000 units
200,000/8 = 25,000 units ••

First production batch:
• Small/medium OEMs: ZX Spectrum - 10-20K units (Europe: small companies [Sinclair, Dragon] hedged with smaller runs)
• Established: C64, Atari 800 – 50K units (US: vertical integration, established distribution, predictable demand)
• High confidence: 100K+ were rare.
• VDP amortized over 100K, even if first batch is 20K.

Total NRE ~$150–200K ($180K)
• VDP ASIC mask set: ~$100k–$150k (typical 1983 NMOS mask)
• PCB tooling: ~$10k–$20k
• Test fixtures / jigs: ~$10k–$15k
• ROM mask cost: ~$25k–$50k (for 16–32 KB ROM)

Per-unit BOM (1983 OEM, 100K MOQ)
Component   Units per board   Unit cost  Cost per board
6502 CPU    1                 $2.50      $2.50
4164 RAM    8                 $0.70      $5.60
4116 VRAM   8                 $0.40      $3.20
VDP ASIC    1                 $8.00      $8.00
74LS TTL    10                $0.12      $1.20
ROM         1                 $1.50      $1.50
Crystal + passives            $1.20      $1.20
Misc board parts              $2.00      $2.00
TOTAL                                    $25.20

NRE per unit = $180k / 10,000 units ≈ $18/unit
Total per-unit cost (parts + NRE) ≈ $25.20 + $18 ≈ $43.20
Add assembly / packaging / logistics (~$5–7) → ~ $50 per unit ($50 x 10,000 = $500K)
This is historically realistic for a low-cost 1983 home computer.

NRE per unit = $180k / 25,000 units ≈ $7.20/unit
Total per-unit cost (parts + NRE) ≈ $25.20 + $7.20 ≈ $32.40
Add assembly / packaging / logistics (~$5–7) → ~ $38 per unit ($38 x 25,000 = $950K/~1M)

Mass production:
NRE per unit = $180k / 100,000 ≈ $1.80/unit
Total per-unit cost (parts + NRE) ≈ $25.20 + $1.80 ≈ $27/unit
With assembly / packaging (~$5–7) → $32–34 per unit ($35 x 100,000 = $3.5M)

Assembly + casing typically adds ~$5–7/unit, so retail BOM ≈ $35/unit for 100K.

Wafer run cost: each wafer is an incremental cost (~$200–300 for NMOS)
• Most Japanese and US NMOS fabs will allow multiple wafer runs from the same mask set.
• Some extra cost for mask storage (~$1–2k)
